<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-02-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-02-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="219" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d219">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Day</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">White</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-02-03"><hi rend="italic">February 3,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Send by telegraph copy of prohibitive decree. Protest against same. Urge
                            special injustice of application to large amount of fruit in transit.
                            Damages to large amount impending. We consider that Government liable to
                            indemnity to shippers without notice, and for breach of contract for
                            delivery. If not wholly revoked, decree should at least be suspended to
                            avoid destruction of fruit shipped without notice of prohibition.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Day</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Acting.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>